# 3c5a9be2e812474c8548f4614307aaff
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:23
msgid "Frequently Asked Questions"
msgstr ""

# ed8dad97720548af8c2368e899eae194
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:29
msgid ""
"How do you create a raw disk for the cache if all your disks have mounted"
" file systems?"
msgstr ""

# 9d9ff0233b2e443fbc0486aae586748d
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:31
msgid ""
"Create a large file on filesystem (with :manpage:`dd(1)`) and mount it as"
" loopback device. This is accomplished with :manpage:`losetup(8)` on "
"Linux, :manpage:`lofiadm(1m)` on Solaris and Illumos, and "
":manpage:`mdconfig(8)` on FreeBSD."
msgstr ""

# 398e49a5d36440a4b9f93d6791f9609e
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:36
msgid ""
"How do disk I/O errors affect the cache and what does Traffic Server do "
"when a cache disk fails?"
msgstr ""

# 9121d2efad164689b01e38fc6ec3f827
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:38
msgid ""
"If a disk drive fails five successive I/O operations, then Traffic Server"
" considers the drive inaccessible and removes the entire disk from the "
"cache. Normal cache operations continue for all other Traffic Server disk"
" drives."
msgstr ""

# f9aeed7e00e44c50bb6d4ec96162817d
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:44
msgid ""
"If a client disconnects during the time that Traffic Server is "
"downloading a large object, is any of the object saved in the cache?"
msgstr ""

# 221315d8aa884e07898094fa93178938
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:46
msgid ""
"When a client disconnects during an HTTP operation, Traffic Server can "
"continue to download the object from the origin server, using the "
":ref:`background fill feature <background_fill>`. It will continue "
"downloading based on the "
":ts:cv:`proxy.config.http.background_fill_active_timeout` and "
":ts:cv:`proxy.config.http.background_fill_completed_threshold` settings."
msgstr ""

# 484cd696ef79440db19490040dbe8d6f
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:51
msgid ""
"Can Traffic Server cache Java applets, JavaScript programs, or other "
"application files like VBScript?"
msgstr ""

# 1aadb66b5ff542a69624493325817afb
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:53
msgid ""
"Yes, Traffic Server can store and serve Java applets, JavaScript "
"programs, VBScripts, and other executable objects from its cache "
"according to the freshness and cacheability rules for HTTP objects. "
"Traffic Server does not execute the applets, scripts, or programs. These "
"objects run entirely client-side (the system which originated the request"
" for the objects), and do not execute on the server."
msgstr ""

# 2ee59b1497aa4a1d9b9e6e7376b67234
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:61
msgid ""
"In Squid- and Netscape-format log files, what do the cache result codes "
"mean?"
msgstr ""

# 7590f10c1c4d46a9ba0cba521e4335dd
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:63
msgid ""
"This is described in detail in the :ref:`log-formats-squid-format` "
"documentation."
msgstr ""

# ceaab1ba890e47dbb61a8a861d4e19fb
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:66
msgid "What is recorded by the ``cqtx`` field in a custom log file?"
msgstr ""

# 5880516639954a94a5b423a92af13709
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:68
msgid ""
"In *forward proxy mode*, the ``cqtx`` field records the complete client "
"request in the log file (for example, ``GET http://www.company.com "
"HTTP/1.0``)."
msgstr ""

# c2b80812aac042b59f40fb2ff7ddc7ff
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:70
msgid ""
"In *reverse proxy mode*, the ``cqtx`` field records the hostname or IP "
"address of the origin server because Traffic Server first remaps the "
"request as per map rules in the :file:`remap.config` file."
msgstr ""

# a55340230eac468bad40282131ceb9d7
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:75
msgid ""
"Does Traffic Server refresh entries in its host database after a certain "
"period of time if they have not been used?"
msgstr ""

# 72b7db9959634b34954af35be95b7f5b
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:77
msgid ""
"By default, the Traffic Server host database observes the time-to-live "
"(``ttl``) values set by name servers. You can reconfigure Traffic Server "
"to ignore the ``ttl`` set by name servers and use a specific Traffic "
"Server setting instead. Alternatively, you can configure Traffic Server "
"to compare the ``ttl`` value set by the name server with the ``ttl`` "
"value set by Traffic Server, and then use either the lower or the higher "
"value."
msgstr ""

# 6abb740451364168a9c76f571d577e65
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:85
msgid "Refer to :ts:cv:`proxy.config.hostdb.ttl_mode` for more info."
msgstr ""

# 2429636e20b1456b8f14812acf4c236f
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:88
msgid ""
"Can you improve the look of your custom response pages by using images, "
"animated .gifs, and Java applets?"
msgstr ""

# a3bf9d23e6e743ac9ab80e817b947b9e
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:90
msgid ""
"No, because Traffic Server can only respond to clients with a single text"
" or HTML document. As a workaround, however, you can provide references "
"on your custom response pages to images, animated .gifs, Java applets, or"
" objects other than text which are located on a web server. Add links in "
"the body_factory template files in the same way you would for any image "
"in an HTML document (i.e., with the full URL in the ``SRC`` attribute)."
msgstr ""

# df276889594b4113a49c193d0be42356
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:99
msgid ""
"Can Traffic Server run in forward proxy and reverse proxy modes at the "
"same time?"
msgstr ""

# a6b6a959741345bc806eecbc51ae2a9b
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:101
msgid ""
"Yes. When you enable reverse proxy mode, Traffic Server remaps incoming "
"requests according to the map rules in :file:`remap.config`. All other "
"requests that do not match a map rule are served in forward proxy mode."
msgstr ""

# 6ac4d23dcce44a5f9be0ff5b4d7e63b9
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:106
msgid ""
"If you want to run in reverse proxy only mode (wherein Traffic Server "
"does not serve requests that fail to match a map rule), then you must set"
" the configuration variable "
":ts:cv:`proxy.config.url_remap.remap_required` to ``1`` in "
":file:`records.config`."
msgstr ""

# d2fa0e62ef914833a9694383ee6a1a53
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:112
msgid "How do I enable forward proxy mode"
msgstr ""

# cc5d2c82bbd44e49800c2ddc7b16ecc1
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:114
msgid "Please refer to the :ref:`forward-proxy` documentation."
msgstr ""

# 7a111a93dacb46ac9761898ef9168943
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:117
msgid "How do I interpret the Via: header code?"
msgstr ""

# 2b1ec760c4914e1d99df7d983b37a199
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:119
msgid ""
"The ``Via`` header string can be decoded with the `Via Decoder Ring "
"<http://trafficserver.apache.org/tools/via>`_."
msgstr ""

# 55e18f5149924c7fa4930286054765bc
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:121
msgid ""
"The Via header is an optional HTTP header added by Traffic Server and "
"other HTTP proxies. If a request goes through multiple proxies, each one "
"appends its Via header content to the end of the existing Via header. Via"
" header content is for general information and diagnostic use only and "
"should not be used as a programmatic interface to Traffic Server."
msgstr ""

# 56bf4c7b211c4ead8bbfe27fabceff1c
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:123
msgid "The form of the Via header is"
msgstr ""

# bd9f61ddd56040f2ad7f848a01cf8c09
#: ../../appendices/faq.en.rst:125
msgid "Via: <protocol> <proxyname> (<product/version> [<via-codes>])"
msgstr ""

